Turn 70 (Student)
Sure! To tie the per‑page loading spinner to the specific pagination button the user clicks, you can keep a piece of state that records which page is currently loading. Here’s a concise example using React with functional components and hooks:

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function PaginatedList({ fetchPage }) {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);
  const [currentPage, setCurrentPage] = useState(1);
  const [loadingPage, setLoadingPage] = useState(null); // null = no button loading

  // Load the first page on mount
  useEffect(() => {
    loadPage(1);
  }, []);

  const loadPage = async (page) => {
    setLoadingPage(page);          // start spinner for this page
    const result = await fetchPage(page);
    setData(result);
    setCurrentPage(page);
    setLoadingPage(null);        // stop spinner
  };

  const pages = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]; // example page numbers

  return (
    <div>
      <ul>
        {data.map(item => (
          <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <div className="pagination">
        {pages.map(page => (
          <button
            key={page}
            onClick={() => loadPage(page)}
            disabled={loadingPage === page}
            style={{
              margin: '0 4px',
              position: 'relative',
              minWidth: '80px',
            }}
          >
            {loadingPage === page ? (
              // Simple CSS spinner (you can replace with any spinner component)
              <span className="spinner" />
            ) : (
              `Page ${page}`
            )}
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>

      {/* Optional: global spinner for the very first load */}
      {loadingPage === null && data.length === 0 && (
        <div className="global-spinner">Loading…</div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### How it works
1. **`loadingPage` state** – Holds the page number that is currently being fetched. When `null`, no button is showing a spinner.
2. **`loadPage` function** – Sets `loadingPage` to the page being requested, calls the async `fetchPage`, updates the data, then resets `loadingPage` to `null`.
3. **Button rendering** – Each button checks `loadingPage === page`. If true, it shows a spinner (or disables the button) so only the clicked button animates.
4. **Global spinner** – The extra block at the bottom shows a full‑width spinner only when the component mounts and no data is present yet.

